INSERT INTO messages VALUES (371,371,1,0,1,'Rizen','Open Discussion: work','We\'re not certain whether we want to allow for jobs in this game. In the old version of SotF you could go to the restaurant and gain money and experience.\r\n\r\nWe have considered this in SotF2 as well. Here\'s what we\'ve been considering:\r\n\r\n1) Work in restaurant. Uses domestics skill.\r\n\r\n2) Work as entertainer at taverns. Uses a new skill, troubadour or posibly charisma. Charisma might also be used for talking to NPCs.\r\n\r\n3) Apprentice with blacksmith. Uses a new skill, smithing. Smithing might also be used to fix your equipment while in the field.\r\n\r\nWe would entertain other ideas as well, but those were our starter ideas.\r\n\r\nTHE PROBLEM: Economic balance. With literally unlimited money available at these jobs, and unlimited turns, we\'d be thrusting too much money into the economy and the survival aspect of the game disappears.\r\n\r\nOne solution to this problem is to use the bankrolls of the individual amenities to fund the payrolls. However, this then severely limits the buying capacity of those vendors.\r\n\r\nAnother solution is simply not to allow PC jobs at NPC amenities. With the real economy system there are a number of jobs already available: hunter, scavenger, thief, bandit (murderer/thief), trader (when auctions go live later this week), map seller/maker, healer, etc.\r\n\r\nTHE QUESTION: Can any of you think of reasons why or why not to allow jobs? And if we do allow jobs, can you think of a way to implement them without destroying the economy?','2001-05-14 14:52:11');
INSERT INTO messages VALUES (372,371,1,371,2,'lynx','Idea:','Your own shop, it would cost X to open, and you could push X into the shop, which would be its money reserves, and  you could put your items into the shop for X price, and the shop could be like renting a room, giving you a +X in hide','2001-05-14 15:36:19');
